0
a few seconds ago
Python3
Intuition
A version number is made up of multiple revisions separated by dots.
"1.0.3" -> [1, 0, 3]
"1.0.10" -> [1, 0, 10]
Instead of comparing the entire strings, we compare each revision from left to right.

The first revision where the values differ determines which version is greater.

If one version has fewer revisions, every missing revision is considered 0
example
1.0
1.0.0.0

↓

1 0 0 0
1 0 0 0
so they are equal

Approach
Split both version strings using ".".
Convert every revision into an integer.
This automatically removes leading zeros.
Maintain two pointers, one for each version.
While either version still has revisions:
If a pointer has crossed its array, treat its value as 0.
Compare the current revisions.
If one is larger, return immediately.
Otherwise move both pointers forward.
If every revision matches, return
Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n+m)

Space complexity:
O(n+m)

Code
class Solution:
    def compareVersion(self, version1: str, version2: str) -> int:
        list1 = list(map(int, version1.split('.')))
        list2 = list(map(int, version2.split('.')))
        ptr1 = ptr2 = 0
        while ptr1 < len(list1) or ptr2 < len(list2):
            if ptr1 < len(list1): x = list1[ptr1]
            else : x = 0
            if ptr2 < len(list2): y = list2[ptr2]
            else: y = 0
            if x < y: return -1
            if x > y : return 1
            ptr1 += 1
            ptr2 += 1
        return 0
